\right)\ .
\eeq
The dotted crossings mean the matrix (see eq.~(\ref{2.2}))
%//{4.3}
\beq \label{4.3}
\bigg(R^{-1}(x)\frac{d}{dx}R(x)\bigg)_{x=1}=\frac{1}{q-q^{-1}}(PR+R^{-1}P)
=\frac{q+q^{-1}}{q-q^{-1}}\big({\bf 1} -2P^{\Lambda_2}\big),
\eeq
where the following decomposition (\ref{1.3}) of the R-matrix \cite{jimbo3}
and the completeness of the projectors has been used
%
%//{4.2}
\beq \label{4.2}
PR=qP^{2\Lambda_1}-q^{-1}P^{\Lambda_2}.
\eeq
%
Therefore we get (with ${\rm const.}=-1/2(q-q^{-1})/(q+q^{-1})$)
up to terms proportional to the unity operator the Hamiltonian of
eq.~(\ref{1.1}) as a sum of projectors $P^{\Lambda_2}$.

In Appendix A we derive the transfer matrix $\tau$ from a cyclic invariant
vertex model on a torus. Therefrom it it obvious that the transfer matrix
as well as the Hamiltonian (\ref{4.1}) describe models with periodic
boundary conditions. However, the derivation in Appendix~A
relies on methods of topological quantum field theory and here we can give
only a short sketch of this methods. Therefore it seems
worthwhile to present a direct proof of this fact.
We denote the Hamiltonian of eq.~(\ref{4.1}) by $H_{N\dots 21}$ and
by $H_{1N\dots 2}$ that one obtained by the cyclic permutation
$(N\dots 21)\mapsto(1N\dots 2)$. The physical content is
invariant under this permutation since both Hamiltonians are equivalent
%//{4.3a}
\beq \label{4.3a}
R^{-1}_{(N\dots 2)1}H_{N\dots 21}R_{1(N\dots 2)}=H_{1N\dots 2}
\eeq
where, as a generalization of eq.~(\ref{2.6}), we have introduced the
R-matrices
%//{4.3b}
\beq \label{4.3b}
R_{1(N\dots 2)}\equiv
